<div class="docs-content__header">
  <span class="docs-content__eyebrow">Guides</span>
  <h1 class="docs-content__title">Org Chart Setup</h1>
  <p class="docs-content__description">Structure your agents in hierarchies that control delegation, escalation, and configuration inheritance.</p>
</div>

<div class="prose">
  <h2 id="how-hierarchy-works">How Hierarchy Works</h2>
  <p>Director organizes roles in a tree structure — each role can have a parent and multiple children, forming an org chart. This hierarchy is not just visual: it controls how work flows through your agent team, who can delegate to whom, and where problems escalate when agents get stuck.</p>
  <p>Roles without a parent are <strong>root roles</strong>. These sit at the top of the org chart and typically represent the highest-level supervisors or the roles that interface directly with human operators.</p>

  <h2 id="designing-your-org-chart">Designing Your Org Chart</h2>
  <p>Think about your org chart in terms of <strong>responsibility boundaries</strong>. A good hierarchy mirrors how you'd organize a real team:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Top level</strong> — project leads or coordinators that receive goals and break them into tasks</li>
    <li><strong>Middle level</strong> — team leads that manage specific domains (backend, frontend, testing)</li>
    <li><strong>Leaf level</strong> — specialist agents that do the actual implementation work</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Start simple. A single root role with 2–3 direct reports is enough for most projects. Add depth as your operation scales.</p>

  <h2 id="parent-child-relationships">Parent-Child Relationships</h2>
  <p>Set a role's <strong>parent</strong> to place it in the hierarchy. A few rules apply:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>The parent must belong to the same project</li>
    <li>A role cannot be its own parent</li>
    <li>A role cannot be parented to one of its own descendants (no circular hierarchies)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Children inherit their parent's adapter type and configuration by default, so you only need to configure the adapter once at the top of a branch.</p>

  <h2 id="delegation-scope">Delegation Scope</h2>
  <p>The org chart determines who can assign work to whom. When a role creates a task, the assignee must be:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>A <strong>subordinate</strong> — any role below the creator in the hierarchy</li>
    <li>A <strong>sibling</strong> — a role with the same parent</li>
    <li>The <strong>creator itself</strong> — self-assignment is allowed</li>
  </ul>
  <p>This prevents lateral or upward delegation that would bypass the chain of command. A backend engineer cannot assign work to the project lead — it has to go through escalation instead.</p>

  <h2 id="escalation-chains">Escalation Chains</h2>
  <p>When an agent encounters a problem it cannot solve, it escalates. Director walks <em>up</em> the parent chain to find the nearest <strong>online</strong> manager — a parent role whose status is not idle or terminated.</p>
  <p>If no online manager is found in the ancestor chain, the escalation surfaces to the human operator through the dashboard. This ensures no problem gets silently swallowed — it always reaches someone who can act on it.</p>

  <h2 id="configuration-inheritance">Configuration Inheritance</h2>
  <p>Child roles automatically inherit from their parent:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Adapter type and config</strong> — so you only configure the AI connection once per branch</li>
    <li><strong>Working directory</strong> — the <code>effective_working_directory</code> walks up the ancestor chain until it finds a role with one set</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Override either setting on a child role to break inheritance for that branch. This is useful when different parts of your org chart work on different codebases or use different AI providers.</p>

  <h2 id="common-patterns">Common Patterns</h2>

  <h3>Flat team</h3>
  <p>One root coordinator with several specialist agents at the same level. Best for small projects where a single supervisor delegates to a handful of executors.</p>

  <h3>Two-tier management</h3>
  <p>A project lead at the root, team leads in the middle, and specialist agents at the bottom. The team leads break goals into tasks and distribute them to their reports. Good for medium-sized operations where you want domain-specific oversight.</p>

  <h3>Deep specialization</h3>
  <p>Multiple levels of hierarchy with narrow responsibilities at each level. A testing lead manages unit test agents, integration test agents, and performance test agents — each with their own skills and working directories. Use this when different agents need different adapter configurations or skill sets.</p>
</div>
